                    "detailed":  "Kuruvadweep, often called Kuruva Island, is a cluster of river islands formed by the Kabini River. Spread across approximately 950 acres, it is a protected eco-tourism zone managed by the Forest Department. The island ecosystem consists of dense evergreen forest, rich birdlife, medicinal plants, and bamboo bridges. It has been developed as an eco-friendly tourism destination with strictly controlled entry to preserve its natural habitat. Kuruvadweep is closed during monsoon and opened seasonally based on river water levels."
